Step 1. Reasoning

Key psychological mechanisms:
• Exploitation: Participants tend to choose the option with a higher observed (sampled) mean reward.
• Exploration: When there are many future opportunities (high horizon), participants may choose the option with higher uncertainty even if its observed mean is lower.
• Uncertainty in this task is manipulated via forced-choice trials: in unequal conditions one option is sampled once (high uncertainty) and the other three times (low uncertainty). In equal conditions both options are sampled twice.
• The interaction: the final utility for each option is determined by its observed (expected) reward plus, when the horizon is long, an exploration bonus that increases with the option’s uncertainty (i.e. inversely proportional to its forced‐choice count).
• A logistic choice rule then transforms the difference in utilities into a probability of selecting an option.

Mathematical form:
• Let H = 1 when the game horizon is long (horizon = 6 free choices) and 0 otherwise.
• For each option i ∈ {0,1}, define the utility as:
  Uᵢ = expected_rewardᵢ + H · exploration_weight · (sigma/√(nᵢ))
  where sigma = 8 (the fixed standard deviation for outcomes) and nᵢ is the count of forced (information) trials for option i.
• The choice probability is given by a logistic function over the difference in utilities scaled by an inverse temperature parameter beta:
  P(choice = 1) = 1/(1 + exp(– beta · [U₁ – U₀]))

Parameters to be calibrated:
• beta (inverse temperature): determines sensitivity to utility differences. Its range is finite and is set to be, for example, (0.001, 20).
• exploration_weight: modulates the bonus given to an option’s uncertainty (i.e., its higher standard error when fewer forced trials are sampled). Its range is finite, for example (0, 100).

Mapping to observable behavior:
• The model uses the provided expected_reward0 and expected_reward1 values.
• The forced-choice trials (when forced_choice is True) yield the counts n₀ and n₁; these counts are aggregated per game from the earlier forced-choice trials.
• The horizon variable determines whether an exploration bonus is applied.
• The model predicts the binary free-choice decision (variable 'choice') using a logistic function applied to the computed utility difference.

Below is the formal mathematical model specification and learnable variable descriptions.

<MODEL>
H = I(horizon = 6)
U_0 = expected_reward0 + H * exploration_weight * (8 / sqrt(n0))
U_1 = expected_reward1 + H * exploration_weight * (8 / sqrt(n1))
P(choice = 1) = 1 / (1 + exp(- beta * (U_1 - U_0)))
</MODEL>

